# Sourceright Codex instructions

You are working on Sourceright. Treat the current repository as the source of truth.

This planning pack is guidance, not a bulk overlay. Do not blindly copy files from this pack into the repo root. Use it to plan and execute small, reviewable implementation slices.

## Core architectural boundaries

Preserve these boundaries:
- `references.csl.json` is canonical clean bibliographic data.
- `references.verification.json` stores evidence, provenance, provider candidates, confidence, conflicts, review status, and verification metadata.
- `review-queue.jsonl` is operational review work derived from the canonical and sidecar artifacts.
- Provider metadata must not silently overwrite canonical CSL.
- Legal citation records remain separate from academic CSL bibliography records.
- Claim/source/provenance graphs may record support relationships but must not assert claim truth.
- MCP write tools must wait until read-only contracts, schemas, audit logs, dry-run semantics, and explicit apply semantics are stable.

## Repo strategy

The repo has already advanced beyond the original scaffold. Do not bulk-apply old overlay ZIPs. Do not split the crate into a workspace unless explicitly requested after an audit.

Prefer additive changes:
- benchmark harness maturity;
- schemas and validation improvements;
- documentation and worked examples;
- rustdoc/API docs;
- public demo and landing-page polish;
- plugin/provider status matrices;
- case-study fixtures;
- read-only MCP examples;
- launch checklist and positioning.

## Quality gates

After each implementation slice, run the appropriate subset of:
- `cargo fmt --check`
- `cargo clippy --all-targets -- -D warnings`
- `cargo test`
- `cargo check --locked`
- `cargo run --bin sourceright -- bench`
- `cargo run --bin sourceright -- report --json examples/workspace` if applicable
- schema/demo validation scripts if present
- docs build command if present

Do not commit automatically. Summarize changed files, checks run, failures, and deferred work.

## Claims discipline

Use accurate language:
- Good: “technical preview,” “pilot-ready,” “fixture-backed regression benchmark,” “deterministic benchmark scaffold.”
- Avoid unless proven: “production-ready institutional platform,” “SOTA benchmarked performance,” “legal filing compliance system,” “AI detector.”

Keep the benchmark claim separate from the product claim.
